<br>
Combat XP per mob killed is based on your Combat level vs. the mobs level.  If you are combat level 5 and kill a combat level 5 mob, you get 1000 combat XP.  Now, there's an underlying equasion to determine how much XP you'll get for mobs higher or lower than you, but god knows there's no way I'll ever be able to find that post anymore.  Basically, you have a range of mobs that will give anywhere from 1 XP point up to 2000 points per kill, and I know at CLevel 20 it's 7 below for 0 XP, and 7 above for 2000 XP.  <br>
<br>
Anyway, all the numatics aside, getting exploration and trade XP will have absolutely no impact on which mobs give you combat XP, it's strictly based on combat level.  What does this mean?  It means that most smart players will leave combat alone and crank up the exploration and trade XP, get the hull upgrades, get the levels in shields and reactors, and then go back and level in combat.  Yeah, you'll still only be able to use L2 or L3 weapons, but you'll have L4 and L5 shields to keep you protected while you do it.<br>
<br>
This is a perfect strategy, BTW, if you're an explorer.  You can keep up with the need for credits with mining, and since Prospect is limited by Exploration levels, you're set to rock - run up Exploration to L30 by exploring the galaxy, get prospect to L4 or L5, get the best Prospect Skill boosting device you can find (Prospecting devices are INSANELY powerful, it's a huge, night-and-day difference), and mine minerals until you amass a small fortune.  You not only keep getting Exploration XP, but you crank out Trade XP in a hurry.<br>
<br>
Quests:  Yeah, it seems like NPC's are more than happy to send you on suicide runs.  =(  Just ignore them, you don't need to do them right away, although the L30 advancement quests result in nice items, but, they generally require you to have your combat levels at least up to 10-12.<br>
<br>
Exploiding 'roids:  They suck.  Not nearly as bad as the roids that spawn high-level mobs, which is likely what you really ran into.  While mining, have your finger hovering over either cloak or foldspace - when you prospect that first item, be ready to run, you'll have about 1 second to act before the mobs AI kicks in, and it will take 1-4 seconds for it to spin around and get you in it's firing arc, so either cloak, or if cloak isn't high enough to trigger fast, foldspace and cloak.  The mob won't roam around, and usually only has a 3k awareness range, so go mine somewhere else.<br>
<br>
Remember the rules of 'sploders though - and asteroid that has a wrong graphic for it's type (i.e. a regular asteroid that looks like a hydrocarbon deposit) will probably explode.  a hydrocarbon deposit that's a different color from others around it will probably explode, and hulks that are 'too good to be true' and are filled to the brim with L6 and L7 devices will almost certianly explode.  On the flipside, Crystalline Asteroids and gas clouds will never spawn or explode on you, so they are very popular.  Gas clouds inparticular are extremely good because they have lots and lots of a particular  type of resource, and that means huge Trade XP.  However, if you are mining in a gas field, mobs (usually those damn manes) will tend to spawn 1-2k directly behind you.  You have to be on the lookout for 'em and be ready to freewarp out in an instant.<br>
<br>
XP Debt - It reduces itself while offline, and it's a percentage reduction.  Almost all XP debt will be gone within 11-13 hours, so if you're having a bad night, don't sweat it.  I've had times where I've worked up a 40k debt prospecting (in an insanely weird and horribly over-my-level place), and I just kept going, prospecting myself silly until I went to bed.  I put all my toys in the vault, went to bed, and the next day my debt was clear and I sold everything I had gotten the night before for full XP - made 8 trade levels in 5 minutes.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Westwood is insidiously clever with XP Debt.  You can still advance, and you can rid yourself of any debt just by staying offline.  The more cynical among us say it's a clever way to make you want to stay offline for a while, not only saving bandwitdh and server capacity, but you're still paying for the privledge to NOT play.  Regardless, it's nice to basically be able to sleep off XP debt.<br>
<br>
Oh, one last thing - it's tempting, oh so tempting, so clear XP debt by exploring.  DON'T DO IT, *ESPECIALLY* if you are a combat class!  Why?  Exploration XP via nav points is a one-time gig.  Once you get it, it's gone forever.  Don't blow half of it paying off a debt.  Those people that do end up losing, oh, 20k - 40k of Exploration XP toward debt payoff, and that's a ton of Exploration XP you'll never see again.  If you're a warrior, it's even worse, because you can't prospect for Exploration XP.  Work off debt with trade routes or combat if you can, both of those forms of XP are easily replaceable, and ending up your Explore XP at Level 33 instead of L29 or 30 is worth it, IMHO. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ulethav.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lethav</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Contributing Member</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(9/16/02 7:37:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3251.topic&index=33>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Hmm, I would swear that i was killing those mobs, then went off and got a bunch of explore levels, came back to them, and they did not even give 1 exp anymore, and i did not get any combat levels?<br>
